answers.body_markdown:
The reason is `echo` writes the output with a trailing newline character.

If you do an `strace`, you can see this in the `write` system call:-

    $ strace -e write echo $&#39;\n&#39;
    write(1, &quot;\n&quot;, 1
    )                       = 1
    write(1, &quot;\n&quot;, 1
    )                       = 1


As per the manual, you can suppress this using a `-n` switch:-


    $ strace -e write echo -n $&#39;\n&#39;
    write(1, &quot;\n&quot;, 1
    )                       = 1

